She told The Local: ‘We started to point out the window, so that the the stewardess became aware of it, and she looked out of the window and picked up the phone. I don’t know who she called but the plane stopped immediately afterwards.’

A Norwegian spokesman told Reuters that the leak was caused by a problem with a fuel valve.

Norwegian's press spokesman Charlotte Holmbergh Jacobsson told The Local that passengers were never in danger because the fuel leak would have registered on the pilots' instrument panel.

Passengers were taken off the plane, which was taken out of service. The flight departed 19 hours later and the jet was later sent to a maintenance facility in Stockholm.

Norwegian said it did not have more detail about the problem because Boeing is responsible for maintenance of the airline's 787 fleet.

Boeing said it was working with Norwegian Air on the issue. 

